english:
  title: A Memorial on Urgent State Matters
  author: Kim Sok-myeong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    There is a saying: when the sovereign shines bright, his ministers grow virtuous and all affairs flourish; when the sovereign falters, his ministers grow idle and all things fall to ruin.

    Your Highness possesses grave dignity and stands in the prime of life. Long having assumed the throne, you have grown well versed in statecraft. Yet your brilliance has made you trust few men. At times you lend ear to eunuchs, monks, and common rabble. Even when great ministers offer counsel or speak their minds, they must first divine Your Highness's wishes before proceeding. Thus flattery has become the custom and the path of honest speech lies blocked—this is the gravest failure of virtuous governance.

    The realm rests upon the shoulders of officials. Now that reward and punishment lack clarity, ministers both great and small grow negligent in their duties. Military commoners leap suddenly to the rank of minister, while slaves occupy the court itself. The order of governance dissolves into chaos, bringing earthquakes as heaven's rebuke. I humbly urge that you make rewards and punishments certain, and treat rank as sacred.

    In antiquity, when soldiers were recruited, they received farmland, so troops never lacked sustenance and marched without complaint. Now powerful families monopolize thousands of acres while soldiers receive nothing. When conscripted for battle, such men crumble like dust—how could they harbor courage against the enemy? I urge you to restore the ancient practice of granting farmland to recruited soldiers.

    If all those at your left and right, before and behind, are righteous men, with whom could the sovereign conspire toward wrong? Yet eunuchs of low station daily grow familiar with Your Highness, who delights in crude and baseless gossip, keeping vigil through the night and rising only at midday. Thus great ministers are kept distant, wise counsel cannot enter, and heaven responds with winter thunder and trembling earth. The fault lies plainly here. Let each of the Three Palaces retain but ten eunuchs; dismiss the rest. Surround yourself instead with upright men and virtuous scholars.

    The art of governance lies recorded in the Classics and Histories. None speak of establishing order through Buddhist texts. Your Highness trusts Buddhism too greatly; consequently, shaven monks press forward with private petitions. I urge you to cease allowing monks to traverse the inner palace, to reopen the Classics Salon, to daily inquire into the way of rule, to constantly read the words of sages and worthies, and to not permit heterodox teachings to cloud your mind.

    Women's petitions are a great plague upon governance. Now seamstresses and attendants within the inner quarters have been enfeoffed as princesses and estate managers—their presumption exceeds all bounds and gravely undermines the order of rank. I urge that henceforth, save for members of the royal house and meritorious families, none receive noble titles; those already enfeoffed should have their ranks revoked.

    The welfare of the countryside depends upon local magistrates. Though the Ministry and Six Boards have procedures for recommendation, all selection bows to favor and face. Some recommended prove unable to read a single character. I urge that you personally examine candidates, verify name against reality, and punish those who recommend the unfit.

    The ancients said: "In a kingdom without pardons, governance is surely peaceful." To nurture weeds harms the harvest; to benefit the wicked harms the righteous; drought and flood spring from the frequent pardoning of crime. I humbly urge you to cease pardoning the guilty, lest you encourage the wicked in their wickedness.
  footnotes:
    - The 'Three Palaces' (三殿) refers to residences or administrative divisions within the royal palace where eunuchs held positions of influence.
    - The 'Classics Salon' (經筵) was an institution where the king studied with scholars to learn principles of governance from classical texts.
    - The text employs classical political philosophy, particularly Confucian ideas about virtuous leadership and the connection between the ruler's conduct and natural portents like earthquakes and storms.
